🧠 Introduction

Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) is a programming paradigm that organizes code using objects and classes.

Python supports OOP to build:

✔ Scalable applications
✔ Reusable code
✔ Modular systems
✔ Real-world software

---

🔹 What is OOP?

```text id="oop_def"
Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) is a programming approach that models real-world entities as objects containing data and behavior.
```

---

🎯 Why OOP?

✔ Code reusability
✔ Better organization
✔ Easy maintenance
✔ Improved scalability
✔ Real-world modeling

---

🏗️ Core OOP Concepts

| Concept | Purpose |
|----------|----------|
| Class | Blueprint for objects |
| Object | Instance of a class |
| Encapsulation | Data hiding |
| Inheritance | Code reusability |
| Polymorphism | Multiple forms |

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🏛️ 1. Classes and Objects

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔹 What is a Class?

```text id="class_def"
A class is a blueprint used to create objects.
```

---

🔹 What is an Object?

```text id="object_def"
An object is an instance of a class.
```

---

🎯 Real-Life Example

```text id="car_example"
Class  → Car

Objects → BMW, Audi, Tesla
```

---

💻 Creating a Class

```python id="class_example"
class Student:
    pass
```

---

💻 Creating an Object

```python id="object_example"
class Student:
    pass

student1 = Student()

print(student1)
```

---

🔧 Constructor (__init__)

A constructor initializes object attributes.

---

💻 Example

```python id="constructor_example"
class Student:

    def __init__(self, name, age):
        self.name = name
        self.age = age

student1 = Student(
    "Saakshi",
    22
)

print(student1.name)
print(student1.age)
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="constructor_output"
Saakshi
22
```

---

🔹 Instance Methods

Methods define object behavior.

---

💻 Example

```python id="method_example"
class Student:

    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name

    def greet(self):
        print(
            "Hello",
            self.name
        )

student = Student("Alex")

student.greet()
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="method_output"
Hello Alex
```

